### Object Keyword in Kotlin

The `object` keyword is used to declare a singleton class or an anonymous class instance.

---

### Object Declaration (Singleton)

Object declarations create a singleton -- a class with exactly one instance.

```kotlin
object AppConfig {
    val appName = "MyApp"
    val version = "1.0"

    fun printConfig() {
        println("$appName v$version")
    }
}

fun main() {
    println(AppConfig.appName)  // MyApp
    AppConfig.printConfig()     // MyApp v1.0
}
```

---

### Object Expressions (Anonymous Classes)

Object expressions create anonymous instances of classes or interfaces.

```kotlin
interface ClickListener {
    fun onClick()
}

val listener = object : ClickListener {
    override fun onClick() {
        println("Clicked!")
    }
}

fun main() {
    listener.onClick()  // Clicked!
}
```

---

### Anonymous Objects Extending Classes

```kotlin
open class Vehicle(val name: String) {
    open fun start() = println("$name started")
}

fun main() {
    val car = object : Vehicle("Tesla") {
        override fun start() {
            println("$name silently started")
        }
    }
    car.start()  // Tesla silently started
}
```

---

### Object as Return Type

```kotlin
fun createComparator(): Comparator<String> {
    return object : Comparator<String> {
        override fun compare(a: String, b: String): Int {
            return a.length - b.length
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Using Object with Type Inference

```kotlin
val adHoc = object {
    var x: Int = 0
    var y: Int = 0
}

// Only accessible within the local scope
fun main() {
    adHoc.x = 10
    adHoc.y = 20
    println("${adHoc.x}, ${adHoc.y}")
}
```

---

### Object vs Companion Object

| Object Declaration | Companion Object |
|-------------------|------------------|
| Top-level or nested | Inside a class |
| Singleton instance | Associated with the class |
| No relation to a class | Can be accessed via class name |

> **Key Point:** Object declarations are thread-safe singletons created lazily when first accessed. Object expressions create anonymous instances on the fly.

codeExample:
object Counter {
    private var count = 0

    fun increment() = count++
    fun current() = count
    fun reset() { count = 0 }
}

fun main() {
    println(Counter.current())  // 0
    Counter.increment()
    Counter.increment()
    println(Counter.current())  // 2

    // Object expression
    val runnable = object : Runnable {
        override fun run() {
            println("Running in anonymous object")
        }
    }
    runnable.run()
}
